Q12 : what is depepndency inverison principle? 
Ans : depepndency inverison principle states that depends on abstraction not on concretion(means complete methods).
      High level module(class) should not depend on low level module because it will be tighntly coupled so 
      we want that both the modules should depend on abstarction so that they can be loosely coupled.
      So we should ddesign our software in such a way that various modules can be seperated from each other 
      using an abstract layer to bind them together.
      
	  Legacy follows : 
       
      Controller layer------->Service layer-------->Repository layer------->DB(Database)
	  
      but what dependency inversion principle says: that classes should depends on abstraction
	  like this : 
	  
                abstraction/interface    abstraction/interface  
               /                   \     /                  \
              /	                    \   /                    \
	  Controller layer             Service layer             Repository layer---->DB(Database) 
	  
      now here classes are dependent on abstraction.
      	  
      Now a days we write our code like this(currently we are using this in our code) :  
	  The BookingController class depends on the BookingService interface (which is an abstraction), 
	  not on the concrete implementation (BookingServiceImpl).This is exactly in line with the Dependency 
	  Inversion Principle (DIP).
	  
	  
	  code  : 
	  // Abstraction (Interface)
		public interface BookingService {
			void bookRoom();
		}

		// Service Implementation
		public class BookingServiceImpl implements BookingService {
			private final BookingRepository repository;

			public BookingServiceImpl(BookingRepository repository) {
				this.repository = repository;
			}

			@Override
			public void bookRoom() {
				repository.saveBooking();
			}
		}

		// Repository Abstraction
		public interface BookingRepository {
			void saveBooking();
		}

		// Repository Implementation
		public class BookingRepositoryImpl implements BookingRepository {
			@Override
			public void saveBooking() {
				System.out.println("Booking saved in DB");
			}
		}

		// Controller Layer
		public class BookingController {
			private final BookingService bookingService;

			public BookingController(BookingService bookingService) {
				this.bookingService = bookingService;
			}

			public void handleRequest() {
				bookingService.bookRoom();
			}
		}

		// Main Class (Dependency Injection)
		public class Main {
			public static void main(String[] args) {
				BookingRepository repository = new BookingRepositoryImpl();
				BookingService service = new BookingServiceImpl(repository);
				BookingController controller = new BookingController(service);

				controller.handleRequest(); // Loose coupling maintained
			}
		}


Q13: why depepndency inverison principle important and what benefits we are getting ? 
Ans - Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) is important because it promotes loose coupling between modules, 
      improving flexibility, testability, and maintainability by relying on abstractions instead of concrete 
      implementations.
	  
	  By applying the Dependency Inversion Principle, the benefits we are getting are :

		Loose Coupling: Modules can be changed independently.
		Better Testability: Easily mock dependencies for testing.
		Improved Maintainability: Simplifies updates and reduces code impact.
		Reusability: Abstractions make components more reusable.
		
| Principle                                         | Short Interview Answer                                                                                                            |
| ------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **S** – **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)** | A class should do **only one job**. It should have **one reason to change**.                                                      |
| **O** – **Open/Closed Principle (OCP)**           | Code should be **open for extension but closed for modification**. We should add new features **without changing existing code**. |
| **L** – **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)**   | Subclasses(childclass) should **replace** their parent classes **without breaking** the application.                              |
| **I** – **Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)** | Don’t force a class to implement **unused methods**. Use **small, specific interfaces**.                                          |
| **D** – **Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)**  | Code should depend on **abstractions (interfaces)**, not on **concrete classes**.                                                 |
		